description: PUH-BrianMartell The Weyl group of E8 has order ≈ 6.96 × 10¹¹ — enormous. Direct scan over all 8D Cartan directions is impossible. Weyl-reduced scan restricts to the fundamental Weyl chamber (a tiny cone where all root projections are non-negative) and accounts for reflections automatically. Simple picture: •  Fundamental chamber: Directions h where r_i · h ≥ 0 for all positive roots. •  Scan only inside chamber — equivalent directions outside are reflections. •  For each h in chamber, compute q_i = r_i · h, filter stable charged (even-integer q_i ≠ 0), count M(h). •  Peaks in chamber = unique embeddings (up to Weyl symmetry). Code design: •  Generate 240 E8 roots. •  Sample h uniformly in fundamental chamber (use rejection or symmetry coordinates). •  Compute multiplicity M(h). •  Visualize landscape — peaks indicate stable directions. This makes uniqueness testable and efficient.
